

### 1️⃣ free – Quick Memory Overview


free -h

Columns:
 total → total installed RAM
 used → used memory
 free → unused memory
 shared → memory shared between processes
 buff/cache → buffers + cache
 available → memory available for new apps

Options:
| Option         | Description                 |
| -------------- | --------------------------- |
| -h           | Human-readable (KB, MB, GB) |
| -m           | Show in MB                  |
| -g           | Show in GB                  |
| -s <seconds> | Repeat every N seconds      |

---

### 2️⃣ vmstat – Memory + System Stats

vmstat 2 5


Columns:

 procs: r (running), b (blocked)
 memory: swpd (swap used), free, buff, cache
 swap: si (swap in), so (swap out)
 io: bi (block in), bo (block out)
 cpu: us, sy, id, wa, st

Options:

| Option | Description         |
| ------ | ------------------- |
| -s   | Show memory summary |
| -m   | Show memory in MB   |

---

### 3️⃣ /proc/meminfo – Detailed Memory Info


cat /proc/meminfo


Key fields:

 MemTotal → total RAM
 MemFree → free RAM
 Buffers → memory for kernel buffers
 Cached → cached pages
 SwapTotal / SwapFree → swap memory
 Active / Inactive → active/inactive pages

Filter example:


grep -E 'MemTotal|MemFree|Buffers|Cached' /proc/meminfo


---

### 4️⃣ top – Real-time Memory Usage


top

 Sort by memory: press M
 Shows:

   VIRT → virtual memory used
   RES → resident memory in RAM
   SHR → shared memory
   %MEM → percentage of total RAM

---

### 5️⃣ htop – Interactive Memory Monitor


htop

 Visual RAM + swap bars
 Sort processes by memory usage (F6 → Memory)
 Color-coded for easy reading

---

### 6️⃣ sar -r – Memory Usage History


sar -r 1 5


 Shows:

   kbmemfree → free RAM
   kbmemused → used RAM
   %memused → percent RAM used
   kbbuffers → buffer memory
   kbcached → cached memory
   kbcommit → committed virtual memory

---

### 7️⃣ smem – Per-Process Memory


smem -k

 Shows memory usage for each process
 Types:

   RSS → Resident Set Size
   USS → Unique Set Size
   PSS → Proportional Set Size

---

### 8️⃣ watch free -h – Live Memory Monitoring


watch free -h

 Refreshes memory stats every 2 seconds (default)
 Good for monitoring memory spikes live

---

# ✅ Summary Table – Memory Commands

| Command             | Description                         | Key Options                      |
| ------------------- | ----------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| free              | Total, used, free, available memory | -h, -m, -g, -s           |
| vmstat            | Memory + system stats               | <interval> <count>, -s, -m |
| cat /proc/meminfo | Detailed low-level memory info      | Use grep to filter fields      |
| top               | Real-time memory usage per process  | M to sort by memory            |
| htop              | Interactive memory monitor          | F6 to sort by memory, live bars  |
| sar -r            | Historical memory usage             | <interval> <count>, -f       |
| smem              | Per-process memory usage            | -k, -m                       |
| vmstat -s         | Memory summary                      | Displays totals                  |
| watch free -h     | Live memory monitoring              | -n <seconds> for interval      |


